	  <title>Exercises: Orientation of Subspaces</title>
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Discuss possible orientations of the subspace <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> consisting of all <math>
                     <latex>(x,y)</latex>
                  </math> with</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>3x+2y</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>We first note that <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math> is the hyperspace of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> perpendicular to the vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{n}=(3,2)</latex>
                     </math>. So it is a line.</para.body>
               </para>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>An orientation of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math> is given by any nonzero vector in <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>. One such vector is</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>:=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>(-2,3)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>For <math>
                        <latex> t&gt;0 </latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>t\cdot \Vect{a}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                     </math> determine the same orientation of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>. On the other hand, if <math>
                        <latex> t&lt;0 </latex>
                     </math>, then <math>
                        <latex>t\cdot \Vect{a}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                     </math> determine opposite orientations of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Discuss possible orientations of the subspace <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> consisting of all <math>
                     <latex>(x,y,z)</latex>
                  </math> with</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>2x - y + 3z</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>x + y + z</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>Begin by finding all those <math>
                     <latex>(x,y,z)</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> which solve the given system of two linear equations.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>The points solving the two equations form a line through the origin in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>The solutions form a 1-dimensional subspace of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>A basis for the solution space is <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{a}:=(-4,1,3)</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>We first determine the solution space <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math> of the given system of two linear equations. Its augmented coefficient matrix is</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>
						
\begin{array}{rrr|r}
2 &amp; -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp;  1 &amp; 1 &amp; 0
\end{array}\quad \overset{\text{RREF}}{\longrightarrow}\quad 
\begin{array}{rrr|r}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; \tfrac{4}{3} &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; -\tfrac{1}{3} &amp; 0
\end{array}

					</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore <math>
                        <latex>(x,y,z)</latex>
                     </math> solves the equations if and only if for an arbitrary number <math>
                        <latex>z</latex>
                     </math>,</para.body>
               </para>
				           <para align="center">
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>x = -\tfrac{4}{3}z</latex>
                     </math>   and   <math>
                        <latex>y = \tfrac{1}{3}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>This happens exactly when</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>(x,y,z) = \left( -\frac{4}{3}\cdot z , \frac{1}{3}\cdot z, z \right) = z\cdot \left( -\frac{4}{3} , \frac{1}{3}, 1 \right)</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Consequently, vectors of the form <math>
                        <latex>t\cdot (-4,1,3)</latex>
                     </math>, with <math>
                        <latex> t&gt;0 </latex>
                     </math>, determine one orientation of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>. If <math>
                        <latex> t&lt;0 </latex>
                     </math> they determine the opposite orientation of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
		    <approach version="2">
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Alternatively, we may argue as follows: The solutions of the first equation form the hyperspace of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> perpendicular to <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{a}:=(2,-1,3)</latex>
                     </math>, and the solutions of the second equation form the hyperspace of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> perpendicular to <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{b}:=(1,1,1)</latex>
                     </math>. So <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math> is the orthogonal complement of <math>
                        <latex>S:=\Set{ \Vect{a},\Vect{b} }</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The vectors <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{b}</latex>
                     </math> are not parallel. So their orthogonal complement in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> has as its basis</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{c}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>:=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{b} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex/>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>(-4,1,3)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Consequently, vectors of the form <math>
                        <latex>t\cdot (-4,1,3)</latex>
                     </math>, with <math>
                        <latex> t&gt;0 </latex>
                     </math>, determine one orientation of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>. If <math>
                        <latex> t&lt;0 </latex>
                     </math> they determine the opposite orientation of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Discuss possible orientations of the subspace <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
